Cédric Beust ♔ wrote:

&gt; The point was that letting the method throw and declare the exception in the
&gt; throws clause is not considered the best way to test for exceptions.

It&#39;s /no/ way to test for exceptions. How would I write an assertion? :) 
(I imagine that was your point.)

&gt; Of course, all of this is moot with JUnit4 / TestNG :-)
...unless you want to check the exception /object/ and not just its 
type. The best I&#39;ve seen for that so far is the block idiom:

assertThrows(closure, expectedException);

where closure is

new ExceptionalClosure() {
     public void execute() throws Exception {
         // code that might throw an exception here
     }
}

and assertThrows does what you&#39;d expect:

public void assertThrows(ExceptionalClosure closure, Exception expected)  {
     try {
         closure.execute();
         fail(&quot;Closure should have thrown an exception, but didn&#39;t.&quot;);
     }
     catch (Exception caught) {
         assertEquals(&quot;Caught different exception&quot;, expected, caught);
     }
}

Conceptually, it&#39;s simpler, but syntax-wise, it sucks. In a language 
that treats code blocks with respect, it&#39;d be better.
